$num = random(2,5,1);
$A = $num**2;
$ans5 = $num/sqrt(pi);
$r = round($ans5*10000)/10000;

$ans1 = "pi r^2";
$ans3 = "pi (r+1)^2";
$ans4 = "pi r^2 + 1";

$ml = new_match_list();
$ml -> qa ( "\( f(r+1) \)",
   "The area of a circle whose radius is 1 cm. more than $BITALIC r${EITALIC}.",
            "\( f(r) + 1 \)",  
   "One more square cm. than the area of a circle with radius 
      $BITALIC r${EITALIC}.");

$ml ->extra("One cm. more than the area of circle with radius 
                   $BITALIC r${EITALIC} square cm.",
            "The radius of a circle whose area is one square cm. more than the
                   area of a circle with radius $BITALIC r${EITALIC}.");
$ml ->choose(2);
$ml->choose_extra(2);
$ml->makeLast("None of the above.");


BEGIN_TEXT
Question 34:
$BR $SPACE $BR
The area, in square centimeters, of a circle whose radius is $BITALIC r $EITALIC cm is given by \( \ A= \pi r^2 \ \) $SPACE .
$BR $SPACE $BR
a) Write this formula using function notation, where \( \ f  \ \) is the name of the function. $BR
\( \ \ \ \ f(r) = \) \{ ans_rule(30) \} 
$BR $SPACE $BR
b) Evaluate \( f(0) = \) \{ ans_rule(20) \} 
$BR $SPACE $BR
c) Evaluate and simplify the formula for \( \ f(r+1) = \) \{ ans_rule(25) \}
$BR $SPACE $BR
d) Evaluate and simplify the formula for \( \ f(r)+1 = \) \{ ans_rule(25) \}
$BR $SPACE $BR
e) Evaluate, and \{ htmlLink("javascript:unitspopup()","INCLUDE UNITS") \} in your answer: \( \ f^{-1}($A) = \) \{ ans_rule(30) \}
$BR $SPACE $BR
f) For each of the mathematical expressions below, match one of the statements A - E below which best explains its meaning in practical terms. $BR
\{ $ml -> print_q \}
\{$ml -> print_a \}


END_TEXT

ANS(fun_cmp( $ans1, vars=>'r' ) );
ANS(num_cmp( 0 ) );
ANS(fun_cmp( $ans3, vars=>'r' ) );
ANS(fun_cmp( $ans4, vars=>'r' ) );
ANS(num_cmp( $ans5, units=>'cm' ) );
ANS(str_cmp( $ml->ra_correct_ans )   ) ;

SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$BR $SPACE $BR 
$BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD
$BR 
a) \( \ \ A = f(r) = \pi r^2 \)
$BR $SPACE $BR
b) \( \ \ f(0) = \pi 0^2 = 0 \)
$BR $SPACE $BR
c) \( \ \ f(r+1) = \pi (r+1)^2 \)
$BR $SPACE $BR
d) \( \ \ f(r) + 1 = \pi r^2 + 1 \)
$BR $SPACE $BR
e) \( \ \ f^{-1}($A) \) means we need to find the radius (in cm), $BITALIC r${EITALIC}, of a circle which has area $A square cm.  Therefore we set \( f(r) = $A \) and solve for $BITALIC r${EITALIC}: $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ \pi r^2 = $A \) $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ r^2 = \frac{$A}{\pi} \) $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ r = \sqrt{ \frac{$A}{\pi} } \) $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ r = \frac{$num}{\sqrt{\pi}} \approx $r \) $BR
Since this number is the corresponding radius (in cm) of a circle which has area $A square cm, the we have \( f^{-1}($A) \approx $r \) cm.
$BR $SPACE $BR
f) The expression \( \ f(r + 1) \ \) is the area of a circle whose radius is
1 cm more than $BITALIC r${EITALIC}. $BR
The expression \( \ f(r) + 1 \ \) is is the area of a circle of radius $BITALIC r${EITALIC}, plus 1 square centimeter more.
$BR
END_SOLUTION
      
